Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.721 --> 00:00:01.970
ADAM CARPENTER: Hi, everybody.

00:00:01.970 --> 00:00:03.740
Welcome back from break.

00:00:03.740 --> 00:00:06.350
My name is Adam Carpenter, and
I lead Google Play's Developer

00:00:06.350 --> 00:00:07.790
Business Growth Initiative.

00:00:07.790 --> 00:00:08.600
MOONLIT BESHIMOV:
And I'm Moonlit.

00:00:08.600 --> 00:00:11.090
I'm a Business Development
Manager at Google Play Games.

00:00:11.090 --> 00:00:11.760
ADAM CARPENTER:
Over the next hour,

00:00:11.760 --> 00:00:13.343
you're going to hear
a number of talks

00:00:13.343 --> 00:00:16.880
about how to optimize your
game's post-launch performance.

00:00:16.880 --> 00:00:18.380
In this session,
we're going to talk

00:00:18.380 --> 00:00:21.644
about identifying opportunities
in your game's data.

00:00:21.644 --> 00:00:23.060
First, we're going
to show you how

00:00:23.060 --> 00:00:25.400
to structure a nimble
product team that's empowered

00:00:25.400 --> 00:00:27.274
to make data-driven decisions.

00:00:27.274 --> 00:00:29.190
MOONLIT BESHIMOV: Second,
from our experiences

00:00:29.190 --> 00:00:31.350
of working with, and
for each of us, part

00:00:31.350 --> 00:00:33.980
of Google top game
developers, what

00:00:33.980 --> 00:00:37.100
are the top five analytics
questions to gauge your game's

00:00:37.100 --> 00:00:37.839
performance.

00:00:37.839 --> 00:00:40.130
ADAM CARPENTER: And last,
why a culture of transparency

00:00:40.130 --> 00:00:43.207
will be critical to your
game's success and growth.

00:00:43.207 --> 00:00:44.540
MOONLIT BESHIMOV: Let's dive in.

00:00:44.540 --> 00:00:46.850
In my years working
the gaming industry,

00:00:46.850 --> 00:00:49.580
it's clear that to improve
a game's performance,

00:00:49.580 --> 00:00:53.210
we must first understand your
players' behavior through data.

00:00:53.210 --> 00:00:56.540
But the question is, what's
the right data to track?

00:00:56.540 --> 00:00:59.480
Adam, in your experience,
what's that one piece of advice

00:00:59.480 --> 00:01:01.340
you give to a new developer?

00:01:01.340 --> 00:01:03.200
ADAM CARPENTER:
Record everything.

00:01:03.200 --> 00:01:06.690
And I know this gets said a
lot, but it's very, very true.

00:01:06.690 --> 00:01:09.110
Your players' kind of
engagement, participation data,

00:01:09.110 --> 00:01:12.710
it's absolutely priceless, and
it's impossible to recreate.

00:01:12.710 --> 00:01:15.330
If you're not recording it
when the actions are happening,

00:01:15.330 --> 00:01:17.100
there's no way to get it back.

00:01:17.100 --> 00:01:18.830
So even if you're
a tiny developer,

00:01:18.830 --> 00:01:21.140
and you're unable to leverage
many of the third party

00:01:21.140 --> 00:01:23.180
analytics solutions
that are out there,

00:01:23.180 --> 00:01:26.400
at least try to record your
data into a flat file format.

00:01:26.400 --> 00:01:28.220
If you have it
saved off somewhere,

00:01:28.220 --> 00:01:30.800
you can always eventually suck
it up into a data warehouse,

00:01:30.800 --> 00:01:33.290
begin to slice and
dice it, and understand

00:01:33.290 --> 00:01:36.170
where your players find
value, and what opportunities

00:01:36.170 --> 00:01:38.229
exist to grow your business.

00:01:38.229 --> 00:01:40.520
MOONLIT BESHIMOV: Assuming
you are recording everything

00:01:40.520 --> 00:01:43.895
and making it accessible,
but the data cannot interpret

00:01:43.895 --> 00:01:45.430
itself.

00:01:45.430 --> 00:01:48.140
To draw the right insights
and create right action plans

00:01:48.140 --> 00:01:50.000
based on these
insights, you need

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:53.090
to have the right people
in the right structure.

00:01:53.090 --> 00:01:56.000
So the next step is to
build the right team.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:01:58.160
In my experience,
many developers

00:01:58.160 --> 00:02:01.140
set up their product
management and analysts teams

00:02:01.140 --> 00:02:03.620
in what I call a classic model.

00:02:03.620 --> 00:02:07.100
In this team structure, you
have the PMs sit in one group,

00:02:07.100 --> 00:02:09.530
and analysts sit in a
completely separate group.

00:02:09.530 --> 00:02:10.250
ADAM CARPENTER:
Maybe it's a case

00:02:10.250 --> 00:02:12.250
of the analysts being
part of a central services

00:02:12.250 --> 00:02:14.240
team, while the PMs,
they're embedded

00:02:14.240 --> 00:02:16.520
within the game team itself.

00:02:16.520 --> 00:02:19.640
In some other scenarios, both
the analysts and the PMs,

00:02:19.640 --> 00:02:21.860
they're integrated
within to the game team.

00:02:21.860 --> 00:02:24.050
But unfortunately,
they might have

00:02:24.050 --> 00:02:27.110
different leaders who have
completely different agendas.

00:02:27.110 --> 00:02:29.515
MOONLIT BESHIMOV: Does this
sound familiar to anyone?

00:02:29.515 --> 00:02:30.890
ADAM CARPENTER:
In this setup, it

00:02:30.890 --> 00:02:33.320
might feel like there's
this huge, monolithic wall

00:02:33.320 --> 00:02:34.980
in between the two groups.

00:02:34.980 --> 00:02:38.540
PMs, they're not able or
willing to play with the data,

00:02:38.540 --> 00:02:40.940
and the analysts, while
they have access to data,

00:02:40.940 --> 00:02:43.282
they're not empowered
to drive any change.

00:02:43.282 --> 00:02:44.990
MOONLIT BESHIMOV: In
this team structure,

00:02:44.990 --> 00:02:48.170
it often feels like PMs will
throw a question over the wall,

00:02:48.170 --> 00:02:50.450
letting analysts work
on it for some time,

00:02:50.450 --> 00:02:52.660
and just wait for
the final answer.

00:02:52.660 --> 00:02:55.250
Then, depending on how
well-formed the question is,

00:02:55.250 --> 00:02:57.890
or what the request is,
the analysts' answer

00:02:57.890 --> 00:02:59.600
can vary a lot.

00:02:59.600 --> 00:03:01.490
ADAM CARPENTER: Sometimes
it's meaningful,

00:03:01.490 --> 00:03:03.620
other times it's
just a data dump.

00:03:03.620 --> 00:03:06.680
And then in some cases, it
takes so long for the analysts

00:03:06.680 --> 00:03:09.350
to generate an answer, that
the PMs have completely

00:03:09.350 --> 00:03:12.055
moved on by the time
they get their response.

00:03:12.055 --> 00:03:13.430
MOONLIT BESHIMOV:
Setup like this

00:03:13.430 --> 00:03:15.560
can create a whole
lot of problems

00:03:15.560 --> 00:03:17.300
that are counterproductive
to having

00:03:17.300 --> 00:03:20.750
an agile, collaborative,
and responsive team.

00:03:20.750 --> 00:03:23.120
Too often than we'd
like, both parties

00:03:23.120 --> 00:03:26.232
might think that thinking the
worst about their counterparts.

00:03:26.232 --> 00:03:27.190
ADAM CARPENTER: Mm-hmm.

00:03:27.190 --> 00:03:29.202
PMs will often wonder
why it takes so long,

00:03:29.202 --> 00:03:31.160
and when they do get an
answer, it isn't really

00:03:31.160 --> 00:03:32.480
what they're looking for.

00:03:32.480 --> 00:03:34.021
And then analysts,
on the other hand,

00:03:34.021 --> 00:03:36.980
they're often really frustrated
by the poorly-formed questions

00:03:36.980 --> 00:03:39.050
they get from PMs,
and they're often

00:03:39.050 --> 00:03:41.990
left wondering if the PMs
are just asking questions

00:03:41.990 --> 00:03:43.491
to waste their time.

00:03:43.491 --> 00:03:44.990
MOONLIT BESHIMOV:
On both sides, you

00:03:44.990 --> 00:03:48.230
have people thinking those
on the other side of the wall

00:03:48.230 --> 00:03:50.380
just don't get the business.

00:03:50.380 --> 00:03:52.520
Adam, do you have
any suggestions?

00:03:52.520 --> 00:03:55.280
ADAM CARPENTER: So if you want
a small and nimble team, one

00:03:55.280 --> 00:03:57.590
that's really empowered to
drive meaningful change--

00:03:57.590 --> 00:04:01.220
business performance --break
away from the standard model.

00:04:01.220 --> 00:04:04.250
Get rid of that wall between
your PMs and your analysts.

00:04:04.250 --> 00:04:06.170
And in fact, I'll
go one step further.

00:04:06.170 --> 00:04:08.350
Get rid of the concept
that PMs and analysts

00:04:08.350 --> 00:04:10.190
need to be separate people.

00:04:10.190 --> 00:04:12.110
For most of us game
devs, we're not

00:04:12.110 --> 00:04:14.000
trying to make tiny
poor performance

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:15.530
improvements to our titles--

00:04:15.530 --> 00:04:17.450
changes which require
a tease test just

00:04:17.450 --> 00:04:19.579
to know if the results
are significant.

00:04:19.579 --> 00:04:21.769
To use a baseball
analogy, we're at bat,

00:04:21.769 --> 00:04:23.460
and we're swinging
for singles, doubles,

00:04:23.460 --> 00:04:25.550
and the occasional home run.

00:04:25.550 --> 00:04:28.490
Results, which when viewed in
the context of an A/B test,

00:04:28.490 --> 00:04:30.684
are immediate and obvious.

00:04:30.684 --> 00:04:32.600
MOONLIT BESHIMOV: What
we're referring to here

00:04:32.600 --> 00:04:35.960
is a hybrid model where
your PM and analyst

00:04:35.960 --> 00:04:37.970
the very same person.

00:04:37.970 --> 00:04:40.610
This role structure can
unleash their potential

00:04:40.610 --> 00:04:44.584
by giving them autonomy,
domain expertise, and purpose.

00:04:44.584 --> 00:04:46.500
ADAM CARPENTER: Set your
PM/analyst hybrids up

00:04:46.500 --> 00:04:49.520
so they own a critical
vertical in the game,

00:04:49.520 --> 00:04:51.400
and then empower them.

00:04:51.400 --> 00:04:53.580
Look to your PMs
to write queries,

00:04:53.580 --> 00:04:55.700
retrieve the data,
slice and dice

00:04:55.700 --> 00:04:59.060
it to form a complete and full
understanding of the problem,

00:04:59.060 --> 00:05:01.850
as well as a hypothesis
about what the solution is.

00:05:01.850 --> 00:05:03.900
Then have them partner
with your engineers,

00:05:03.900 --> 00:05:05.900
your creative
designers, your artists

00:05:05.900 --> 00:05:07.400
to come up with a solution.

00:05:07.400 --> 00:05:09.260
And once the solution
has been implemented--

00:05:09.260 --> 00:05:11.300
the new feature --own it.

00:05:11.300 --> 00:05:13.290
Monitor the results post-launch.

00:05:13.290 --> 00:05:15.170
Make sure you're
iterating, and optimizing,

00:05:15.170 --> 00:05:17.240
and constantly trying
to improve and identify

00:05:17.240 --> 00:05:19.312
vectors for change.

00:05:19.312 --> 00:05:21.770
MOONLIT BESHIMOV: In summary,
to empower your team members,

00:05:21.770 --> 00:05:24.920
give them real ownership
over the product roadmap,

00:05:24.920 --> 00:05:28.550
and the ability to conduct
hypothesis-driven testing.

00:05:28.550 --> 00:05:31.280
Give them the freedom to
choose the resources to let

00:05:31.280 --> 00:05:34.880
them work on improving
your game's performance.

00:05:34.880 --> 00:05:37.670
Now suppose you have
the right team in place.

00:05:37.670 --> 00:05:39.740
To unleash their
potential, leverage

00:05:39.740 --> 00:05:42.614
the power of innate curiosity.

00:05:42.614 --> 00:05:44.030
ADAM CARPENTER:
Empower your team,

00:05:44.030 --> 00:05:46.405
and encourage them to ask
critical questions about what's

00:05:46.405 --> 00:05:48.470
actually happening in your game.

00:05:48.470 --> 00:05:50.553
MOONLIT BESHIMOV: One of
the most frequently asked

00:05:50.553 --> 00:05:52.100
questions I get
from my developers

00:05:52.100 --> 00:05:54.860
is that we track and
see a lot of data.

00:05:54.860 --> 00:05:58.010
But what questions do we ask
to understand if our game is

00:05:58.010 --> 00:05:59.950
actually performing well?

00:05:59.950 --> 00:06:01.970
Here's some to get you started.

00:06:01.970 --> 00:06:05.390
But most importantly, take
these as the inspiration

00:06:05.390 --> 00:06:07.610
for the type of data
you ask your team,

00:06:07.610 --> 00:06:09.111
and for your team
to ask themselves.

00:06:09.111 --> 00:06:11.026
ADAM CARPENTER: Consider
how your new installs

00:06:11.026 --> 00:06:11.700
are performing.

00:06:11.700 --> 00:06:14.030
Are they returning the day
after their first session?

00:06:14.030 --> 00:06:16.430
And if they are, how much time
are they actually spending

00:06:16.430 --> 00:06:17.750
playing the game?

00:06:17.750 --> 00:06:20.960
Likewise, think about how we can
better quantify and understand

00:06:20.960 --> 00:06:23.900
what brings players back to
the game each and every day,

00:06:23.900 --> 00:06:27.350
and when they do return, where
are they perceiving value?

00:06:27.350 --> 00:06:29.930
Additionally, think about
drilling deeper and deeper

00:06:29.930 --> 00:06:32.960
into the metrics, and moving
away from lagging indicators

00:06:32.960 --> 00:06:34.580
like revenue and DAU.

00:06:34.580 --> 00:06:38.180
Instead try to focus on finding
meaningful participation

00:06:38.180 --> 00:06:41.510
metrics which can serve
as leading indicators.

00:06:41.510 --> 00:06:44.630
MOONLIT BESHIMOV: Let's take a
look at our top five in detail.

00:06:44.630 --> 00:06:47.270
For those of you who
attended our Playtime event

00:06:47.270 --> 00:06:49.520
or read our Medium
article, you may

00:06:49.520 --> 00:06:52.610
be familiar with the concept
that your players' first 10

00:06:52.610 --> 00:06:55.460
minutes in your game
is an early indicator

00:06:55.460 --> 00:06:57.530
of the next-day retention.

00:06:57.530 --> 00:06:59.750
We recommend that you
plot the following graph.

00:06:59.750 --> 00:07:02.130
On the x-axis, you
have the average number

00:07:02.130 --> 00:07:04.550
of minutes your players
spend in your game

00:07:04.550 --> 00:07:06.440
on their very
first day, against,

00:07:06.440 --> 00:07:08.930
on the y-axis, the
percentage of players

00:07:08.930 --> 00:07:10.795
who come back on day two.

00:07:10.795 --> 00:07:12.920
ADAM CARPENTER: Usually
what we would expect to see

00:07:12.920 --> 00:07:14.930
is that with each
successive minute played,

00:07:14.930 --> 00:07:18.050
a greater percentage of
users are likely to return.

00:07:18.050 --> 00:07:20.210
However using
Google Play's data,

00:07:20.210 --> 00:07:24.620
we've been able to identify two
negative patterns in the game,

00:07:24.620 --> 00:07:26.427
that when you look at
your own game data,

00:07:26.427 --> 00:07:28.760
you can identify opportunities
for growing and improving

00:07:28.760 --> 00:07:30.110
your retention.

00:07:30.110 --> 00:07:32.390
The first pattern,
which we call the flats,

00:07:32.390 --> 00:07:35.042
retention is largely flat for
the first 5 to 10 minutes.

00:07:35.042 --> 00:07:36.500
And the second
pattern, which we've

00:07:36.500 --> 00:07:38.180
dubbed the gorge,
which you can actually

00:07:38.180 --> 00:07:41.840
see your retention dropping over
the first three to five minutes

00:07:41.840 --> 00:07:43.790
before it begins to rise.

00:07:43.790 --> 00:07:46.490
If you see either of these
two patterns in your own data,

00:07:46.490 --> 00:07:48.740
it suggests that there are
significant opportunities

00:07:48.740 --> 00:07:50.475
to improve your early retention.

00:07:50.475 --> 00:07:51.850
MOONLIT BESHIMOV:
To all the PMs,

00:07:51.850 --> 00:07:55.340
analysts, and business owners in
the audience, plot this graph.

00:07:55.340 --> 00:07:58.530
And if your see either of
these improvement signals,

00:07:58.530 --> 00:08:01.820
be very curious what's
actually causing it.

00:08:01.820 --> 00:08:04.230
Is it a very large
secondary download?

00:08:04.230 --> 00:08:05.900
Is it your tutorial?

00:08:05.900 --> 00:08:07.680
Is it the very confusing lobby?

00:08:07.680 --> 00:08:09.780
Or maybe you are overly
aggressive in terms

00:08:09.780 --> 00:08:13.190
monetization in the first
five minutes of game play.

00:08:13.190 --> 00:08:15.680
All of these can heavily
impact your first-time user

00:08:15.680 --> 00:08:19.148
experience, and thus
lower your retention.

00:08:20.867 --> 00:08:22.950
ADAM CARPENTER: After
you've gotten your new users

00:08:22.950 --> 00:08:24.709
to come back over
the first few days,

00:08:24.709 --> 00:08:27.000
think about what's keeping
them there in the long term,

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:29.610
and whether they're spending
more or less time in your game.

00:08:29.610 --> 00:08:31.485
To see that, you can
take a look at the graph

00:08:31.485 --> 00:08:32.549
on the right-hand side.

00:08:32.549 --> 00:08:34.289
What it shows is
the average amount

00:08:34.289 --> 00:08:36.630
of time per user in
the install cohort

00:08:36.630 --> 00:08:38.700
who returned on a given day.

00:08:38.700 --> 00:08:41.700
The x-axis is the number of days
since the user's first session,

00:08:41.700 --> 00:08:43.770
and the y-axis is, again,
that average amount

00:08:43.770 --> 00:08:45.570
of time per active user.

00:08:45.570 --> 00:08:47.180
It's an important
to view, as it's

00:08:47.180 --> 00:08:49.470
going to help you understand
the extent to which

00:08:49.470 --> 00:08:51.900
your new installs are spending
greater or lesser amounts

00:08:51.900 --> 00:08:53.540
of time in your game.

00:08:53.540 --> 00:08:56.220
In almost all the games that
we've looked at, what you see

00:08:56.220 --> 00:08:58.950
is this very sharp rise from
the day one minute to the day

00:08:58.950 --> 00:09:00.150
two minutes.

00:09:00.150 --> 00:09:02.500
This is driven largely by
the low-quality installs

00:09:02.500 --> 00:09:04.490
that you get in that
first day churning out,

00:09:04.490 --> 00:09:06.281
and the users who come
back on the next day

00:09:06.281 --> 00:09:08.154
being exceptionally engaged.

00:09:08.154 --> 00:09:09.570
MOONLIT BESHIMOV:
Past day 10, you

00:09:09.570 --> 00:09:11.940
may see one of the
following three patterns:

00:09:11.940 --> 00:09:15.120
growing, stable, or declining.

00:09:15.120 --> 00:09:17.280
There's no one right
answer to this.

00:09:17.280 --> 00:09:19.940
Most importantly, take
this as a starting point

00:09:19.940 --> 00:09:23.035
to investigate what's
driving user behavior.

00:09:23.035 --> 00:09:24.660
Think about what the
in-game experience

00:09:24.660 --> 00:09:27.150
is like from their perspective.

00:09:27.150 --> 00:09:29.840
For example, if the
minutes per active install

00:09:29.840 --> 00:09:32.160
grows significantly
over time, is it

00:09:32.160 --> 00:09:34.380
because of overall
low retention,

00:09:34.380 --> 00:09:38.130
where only your most loyal
players remain, or is it

00:09:38.130 --> 00:09:41.020
because players think they
have to spend a lot of time

00:09:41.020 --> 00:09:43.380
in your game in
order to succeed?

00:09:43.380 --> 00:09:46.840
On the other hand, you might
have a very amazing feature

00:09:46.840 --> 00:09:51.790
that's only available
after level 20, 30, or 40.

00:09:51.790 --> 00:09:54.150
ADAM CARPENTER: If average
play time is shrinking,

00:09:54.150 --> 00:09:56.040
think about what
might be causing that.

00:09:56.040 --> 00:09:57.312
Is it as case of content?

00:09:57.312 --> 00:09:58.770
Your game just
doesn't have enough,

00:09:58.770 --> 00:10:00.436
and despite the fact
that players really

00:10:00.436 --> 00:10:03.840
want to engage in play, there
isn't enough for them to do.

00:10:03.840 --> 00:10:06.630
Also, think about how your
game economy is structured.

00:10:06.630 --> 00:10:07.470
Is it too tight?

00:10:07.470 --> 00:10:09.050
Are you squeezing your players?

00:10:09.050 --> 00:10:11.324
And are you forcing them
to pay too early such

00:10:11.324 --> 00:10:13.240
that they can't spend
enough time in the game,

00:10:13.240 --> 00:10:15.330
and they're more
likely to churn out.

00:10:15.330 --> 00:10:17.790
We'd strongly encourage you
to go back to your development

00:10:17.790 --> 00:10:20.100
teams, generate plots
like this, and then be

00:10:20.100 --> 00:10:23.100
curious about what's actually
happening in your game, what

00:10:23.100 --> 00:10:24.420
patterns you're seeing.

00:10:24.420 --> 00:10:27.150
Because being curious about how
your new players are engaging

00:10:27.150 --> 00:10:29.700
in the game will set you up
for success by helping you

00:10:29.700 --> 00:10:32.580
understand what gameplay aspects
might be helping or hindering

00:10:32.580 --> 00:10:34.560
your game's performance.

00:10:34.560 --> 00:10:36.780
MOONLIT BESHIMOV: For your
broad DAU base, have you

00:10:36.780 --> 00:10:40.090
thought about what brings
them back each and every day?

00:10:40.090 --> 00:10:43.260
A view we particularly
like, segment your DAU

00:10:43.260 --> 00:10:46.920
based on when your players
were last active in your game.

00:10:46.920 --> 00:10:50.310
For example, take all of
today's DAU, and group them

00:10:50.310 --> 00:10:53.280
based on what percentage
is from new installs.

00:10:53.280 --> 00:10:55.980
What percentage was
active yesterday,

00:10:55.980 --> 00:10:58.920
what percentage was active
two to four days ago,

00:10:58.920 --> 00:11:00.022
so on and so forth.

00:11:00.022 --> 00:11:01.980
ADAM CARPENTER: When
viewing a graph like this,

00:11:01.980 --> 00:11:04.740
what you're trying to do is
maximize the percent of DAU

00:11:04.740 --> 00:11:07.050
who was last active yesterday,
because this would mean

00:11:07.050 --> 00:11:08.924
that a majority of your
users are coming back

00:11:08.924 --> 00:11:11.020
to the game each and every day.

00:11:11.020 --> 00:11:13.590
Now it's unlikely you
will ever get to 100%

00:11:13.590 --> 00:11:15.630
last active yesterday,
but that should

00:11:15.630 --> 00:11:17.790
be all of our stretch goals.

00:11:17.790 --> 00:11:20.430
And for each segment
besides those who are active

00:11:20.430 --> 00:11:22.920
the day before, think
about what their needs are,

00:11:22.920 --> 00:11:24.420
where their interests lie.

00:11:24.420 --> 00:11:27.030
Think about how you can provide
better experiences, better

00:11:27.030 --> 00:11:30.690
incentives to get your players
to return each and every day.

00:11:30.690 --> 00:11:32.664
MOONLIT BESHIMOV: It's
especially important

00:11:32.664 --> 00:11:34.080
to focus on the
group of users who

00:11:34.080 --> 00:11:37.010
are less active two
to four days ago,

00:11:37.010 --> 00:11:40.260
as these are the easiest to
convert to daily players.

00:11:40.260 --> 00:11:41.940
Think about what
incentives can you

00:11:41.940 --> 00:11:45.520
offer to have them come
back each and every day.

00:11:45.520 --> 00:11:47.790
Can you strengthen
your return mechanics?

00:11:47.790 --> 00:11:50.320
Can you personalize
a push notification?

00:11:50.320 --> 00:11:52.770
Or can you leverage
your social system

00:11:52.770 --> 00:11:56.490
to create extremely compelling
experiences to bring them back

00:11:56.490 --> 00:11:59.430
day after day after day?

00:11:59.430 --> 00:12:02.190
ADAM CARPENTER: In addition
to segmenting your users

00:12:02.190 --> 00:12:05.100
by their daily last
active play, you

00:12:05.100 --> 00:12:07.410
can also do the equivalent
thing for your revenue

00:12:07.410 --> 00:12:08.774
and your buyers.

00:12:08.774 --> 00:12:10.940
The charts we're looking
at here show the percentage

00:12:10.940 --> 00:12:12.900
of revenue in the
percent of buyers

00:12:12.900 --> 00:12:15.840
based on when those users
last paid in the game.

00:12:15.840 --> 00:12:18.090
And the way to calculate
this, for example,

00:12:18.090 --> 00:12:19.050
let's say it's today.

00:12:19.050 --> 00:12:21.000
Take all the revenue
you earned from today,

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:23.850
and then segment it,
create sections and slices

00:12:23.850 --> 00:12:26.750
based on when those users
previously paid in the game.

00:12:26.750 --> 00:12:29.070
MOONLIT BESHIMOV: Views
like this are very valuable

00:12:29.070 --> 00:12:32.370
to understand when, where,
and how your players perceive

00:12:32.370 --> 00:12:34.170
value in your game.

00:12:34.170 --> 00:12:38.190
For example, look at this
graph, and ask what percentage

00:12:38.190 --> 00:12:40.180
is your first-time buyers.

00:12:40.180 --> 00:12:41.880
If you are relatively
new game, and you

00:12:41.880 --> 00:12:44.180
see a high percentage
of first-time buyers,

00:12:44.180 --> 00:12:45.910
that's to be expected.

00:12:45.910 --> 00:12:48.580
But this number should be
trending down over time

00:12:48.580 --> 00:12:52.480
as you convert your first-time
buyers into repeated buyers.

00:12:52.480 --> 00:12:54.480
So if you're
relatively mature game

00:12:54.480 --> 00:12:57.810
and you still see a very high
first-time buyer percentage,

00:12:57.810 --> 00:12:59.640
ask yourself what's
incentivizing

00:12:59.640 --> 00:13:02.539
a user to purchase
once, but not again?

00:13:02.539 --> 00:13:04.080
ADAM CARPENTER:
Likewise, take a look

00:13:04.080 --> 00:13:06.310
at the percent of your
daily buyers and revenue

00:13:06.310 --> 00:13:07.976
which is coming from
users who purchased

00:13:07.976 --> 00:13:10.879
in the last week, the last
month, or the last quarter,

00:13:10.879 --> 00:13:13.170
and then think about what's
driving a specific purchase

00:13:13.170 --> 00:13:16.780
frequency, and how players are
perceiving value in your game.

00:13:16.780 --> 00:13:19.410
Think about what causes them to
open up their wallets and pay,

00:13:19.410 --> 00:13:22.705
and when they do, are they
having a good experience?

00:13:22.705 --> 00:13:24.080
Then, see if you
have the ability

00:13:24.080 --> 00:13:26.780
to shift monthly buyers to
weekly, or quarterly buyers

00:13:26.780 --> 00:13:28.110
to monthly.

00:13:28.110 --> 00:13:30.860
If you're able to do this, it'll
help stabilize your revenue

00:13:30.860 --> 00:13:32.960
and make it much
more predictable.

00:13:32.960 --> 00:13:34.460
MOONLIT BESHIMOV:
Finally, we'd like

00:13:34.460 --> 00:13:37.230
to encourage you to move
away from vanity metrics,

00:13:37.230 --> 00:13:39.072
like DAU and revenue.

00:13:39.072 --> 00:13:41.030
While these are important
business metrics that

00:13:41.030 --> 00:13:43.010
measure the health
of your game, they

00:13:43.010 --> 00:13:47.570
are just the end results,
not the leading indicators.

00:13:47.570 --> 00:13:50.774
ADAM CARPENTER: Instead try to
identify a metric or metrics

00:13:50.774 --> 00:13:52.940
which can serve as the most
meaningful and effective

00:13:52.940 --> 00:13:55.700
representation of
engagement in your game.

00:13:55.700 --> 00:13:57.610
Finding the right
participation metric

00:13:57.610 --> 00:13:59.540
will let you identify
issues in the game

00:13:59.540 --> 00:14:02.960
before they begin to
impact revenue and DAU.

00:14:02.960 --> 00:14:05.030
As a broad concept,
participation

00:14:05.030 --> 00:14:06.980
measures the percent
of your DAU who

00:14:06.980 --> 00:14:10.102
are engaging in a critical
action on a given day.

00:14:10.102 --> 00:14:11.810
MOONLIT BESHIMOV: To
give you an example,

00:14:11.810 --> 00:14:15.110
here are the ideas from
three popular genres.

00:14:15.110 --> 00:14:18.260
Much like game developers
use level completion

00:14:18.260 --> 00:14:20.890
as our participation
metric, players

00:14:20.890 --> 00:14:22.730
who have been in
the level or those

00:14:22.730 --> 00:14:24.440
who exit the game
before finishing

00:14:24.440 --> 00:14:26.450
the level don't count.

00:14:26.450 --> 00:14:28.640
Instead, they measure
the number of players

00:14:28.640 --> 00:14:31.400
who played the level all the
way to the end whether they

00:14:31.400 --> 00:14:33.560
pass or fail.

00:14:33.560 --> 00:14:35.930
They use this as a
participation metric,

00:14:35.930 --> 00:14:38.240
because it measures
a player's intent

00:14:38.240 --> 00:14:41.230
to finish the level and
progress in the game.

00:14:41.230 --> 00:14:44.270
It also has the added bonus
of surfacing monetization

00:14:44.270 --> 00:14:46.220
opportunities when
players are out

00:14:46.220 --> 00:14:48.590
of moves and need power-ups.

00:14:48.590 --> 00:14:50.540
ADAM CARPENTER: In games
like slots or bingo--

00:14:50.540 --> 00:14:52.400
social Casino genre,
et cetera, you

00:14:52.400 --> 00:14:55.850
have some very interesting
dynamics in the game economy.

00:14:55.850 --> 00:14:57.350
The way the game
economy works is,

00:14:57.350 --> 00:14:59.558
whether its credits or its
coins, generally speaking,

00:14:59.558 --> 00:15:02.580
players can accumulate a near
unlimited amount of resources.

00:15:02.580 --> 00:15:05.270
So what you actually have is
a relatively large percent

00:15:05.270 --> 00:15:08.280
of the DAU come back everyday
to collect their assets,

00:15:08.280 --> 00:15:10.880
but they never actually consume
or spend any in the game.

00:15:10.880 --> 00:15:12.740
This has led many
slots developers

00:15:12.740 --> 00:15:14.990
to use the notion
that a user who

00:15:14.990 --> 00:15:17.750
sinks coins playing a
slot machine for part

00:15:17.750 --> 00:15:19.160
of their participation metric.

00:15:19.160 --> 00:15:21.590
Or some of the even more
advanced slots developers,

00:15:21.590 --> 00:15:23.210
their participation
metric is actually

00:15:23.210 --> 00:15:25.700
the percent of their DAU
you who goes out of coins

00:15:25.700 --> 00:15:27.047
playing on a given day.

00:15:27.047 --> 00:15:28.880
MOONLIT BESHIMOV: In
mythical strategy games

00:15:28.880 --> 00:15:31.370
like War Dragons,
player interactions

00:15:31.370 --> 00:15:33.040
are very important.

00:15:33.040 --> 00:15:34.750
Paul [? Gayjan, ?]
the game developer,

00:15:34.750 --> 00:15:36.800
tracked the number
of daily attacks

00:15:36.800 --> 00:15:39.470
and participation
in weekly events.

00:15:39.470 --> 00:15:44.480
When during attack, players are
actively engaged in gameplay.

00:15:44.480 --> 00:15:46.940
Attacks also generate
two actions--

00:15:46.940 --> 00:15:49.440
retaliation, and
base repairment.

00:15:49.440 --> 00:15:52.400
Both increase a player's
investment in game and resource

00:15:52.400 --> 00:15:53.630
consumption.

00:15:53.630 --> 00:15:55.400
The same is true
for weekly events.

00:15:55.400 --> 00:15:57.191
ADAM CARPENTER: In all
cases, participation

00:15:57.191 --> 00:15:59.960
is critical, as it measures
the player's intent--

00:15:59.960 --> 00:16:01.790
their desire to play.

00:16:01.790 --> 00:16:04.280
We'd strongly encourage you
to explore your own data,

00:16:04.280 --> 00:16:07.340
and figure out what your
key participation metric is,

00:16:07.340 --> 00:16:10.370
as finding it will help you
better understand your players

00:16:10.370 --> 00:16:12.302
and the overall
health of your game.

00:16:12.302 --> 00:16:14.510
MOONLIT BESHIMOV: Now suppose
you have the right team

00:16:14.510 --> 00:16:17.900
structure, and by leveraging
their innate curiosity,

00:16:17.900 --> 00:16:20.480
you're asking it all
the right questions.

00:16:20.480 --> 00:16:23.210
But how do you find
the right answers?

00:16:23.210 --> 00:16:26.240
The best answers cannot
be discovered in silo,

00:16:26.240 --> 00:16:29.330
and the best solutions
often cover very different

00:16:29.330 --> 00:16:30.680
perspectives.

00:16:30.680 --> 00:16:32.790
To have that
diverse perspective,

00:16:32.790 --> 00:16:35.750
it's important to have
the right team culture.

00:16:35.750 --> 00:16:38.780
So ask this: what is
your team culture?

00:16:38.780 --> 00:16:41.270
Is it open or is it closed?

00:16:41.270 --> 00:16:45.529
Do you hold information tightly,
or do you share it widely?

00:16:45.529 --> 00:16:47.320
ADAM CARPENTER: Sharing
thoughts, findings,

00:16:47.320 --> 00:16:48.540
and insights--

00:16:48.540 --> 00:16:51.260
they're absolutely critical
to your game's success.

00:16:51.260 --> 00:16:55.070
And likewise, how you share
information is important.

00:16:55.070 --> 00:16:57.360
Sharing data alone
is meaningless.

00:16:57.360 --> 00:17:00.080
What you actually need to
do is share information,

00:17:00.080 --> 00:17:01.880
which is data in context.

00:17:01.880 --> 00:17:04.400
For while data by itself
can be interesting,

00:17:04.400 --> 00:17:07.357
information is meaningful
and actionable.

00:17:07.357 --> 00:17:09.440
MOONLIT BESHIMOV: So open
up your weekly analytics

00:17:09.440 --> 00:17:12.710
meetings to all of the key
stakeholders of your business.

00:17:12.710 --> 00:17:15.890
Use these meetings as a
platform to not only discuss

00:17:15.890 --> 00:17:19.250
past updates, events,
and sales, but also

00:17:19.250 --> 00:17:23.255
ask probing questions to each
other, and brainstorm together.

00:17:23.255 --> 00:17:25.130
ADAM CARPENTER: Likewise,
encourage your team

00:17:25.130 --> 00:17:28.040
to make sharing a regular
part of their daily work.

00:17:28.040 --> 00:17:29.480
If they are
investigating an issue

00:17:29.480 --> 00:17:31.580
or trying improve a
feature, encourage

00:17:31.580 --> 00:17:33.920
them to call a peer over,
talk through the trends

00:17:33.920 --> 00:17:36.260
and patterns, understand
what's going on,

00:17:36.260 --> 00:17:38.120
and ultimately
work to understand

00:17:38.120 --> 00:17:41.150
and come up with
effective solutions.

00:17:41.150 --> 00:17:42.860
MOONLIT BESHIMOV:
Now let's summarize.

00:17:42.860 --> 00:17:45.590
What does it take to
identify opportunities

00:17:45.590 --> 00:17:47.294
through games data?

00:17:47.294 --> 00:17:48.710
ADAM CARPENTER:
First, if you want

00:17:48.710 --> 00:17:50.854
to be able to identify
opportunities, the most

00:17:50.854 --> 00:17:52.520
important thing is
to ensure that you're

00:17:52.520 --> 00:17:55.464
recording absolutely everything
that's happening in your game.

00:17:55.464 --> 00:17:57.380
MOONLIT BESHIMOV: Second,
make sure you set up

00:17:57.380 --> 00:17:59.590
an agile team
whose well-equipped

00:17:59.590 --> 00:18:03.050
to not only interpret the
data, but to also take actions

00:18:03.050 --> 00:18:04.580
based on these insights.

00:18:04.580 --> 00:18:06.413
ADAM CARPENTER: And
then encourage your team

00:18:06.413 --> 00:18:08.390
to be curious about
anything and everything.

00:18:08.390 --> 00:18:12.440
Dig through the data, ask
questions, generate insights.

00:18:12.440 --> 00:18:14.670
Always be curious about
what your users are valuing

00:18:14.670 --> 00:18:17.990
in your game, and how you can
use your understanding of that

00:18:17.990 --> 00:18:20.970
to improve your business
and drive long-term growth.

00:18:20.970 --> 00:18:22.490
MOONLIT BESHIMOV:
Finally, encourage

00:18:22.490 --> 00:18:26.250
that culture of sharing at
all levels of your company--

00:18:26.250 --> 00:18:29.469
101, intra-team, as
well as company-wide.

00:18:29.469 --> 00:18:31.760
ADAM CARPENTER: Thank you
guys very much for your time.

