01:01:26.480 --> 01:01:28.430
that level designers
have to think about

01:01:28.430 --> 01:01:30.297
is the balancing of the level.

01:01:30.297 --> 01:01:31.130
What does that mean?

01:01:35.470 --> 01:01:40.820
It means that the level cannot
be too easy, too trivial,

01:01:40.820 --> 01:01:42.114
and it is no--

01:01:42.114 --> 01:01:44.280
there's no challenge, no
stimulation for the player,

01:01:44.280 --> 01:01:47.190
and it cannot be too hard,
because then there is no

01:01:47.190 --> 01:01:49.870
feeling of reward
you feel every time.

01:01:49.870 --> 01:01:52.950
So it's extremely important
to get the right balance

01:01:52.950 --> 01:01:56.640
of difficulty of finding
the just-right difficulty

01:01:56.640 --> 01:01:58.950
for a level.

01:01:58.950 --> 01:02:01.270
So how do we do that?

01:02:01.270 --> 01:02:04.020
This is what we used to do.

01:02:04.020 --> 01:02:08.490
We have level designers think
about the level of creation.

01:02:08.490 --> 01:02:11.130
That takes time-- all
these three elements

01:02:11.130 --> 01:02:13.140
that I mentioned
before --and then

01:02:13.140 --> 01:02:16.560
you send it out for
human play testing.

01:02:16.560 --> 01:02:18.660
And that took seven days.

01:02:21.360 --> 01:02:26.140
So seven days later, we get a
feedback from the play testers,

01:02:26.140 --> 01:02:30.220
and they tell us for
the new 15 levels,

01:02:30.220 --> 01:02:32.590
for example, Level 3
and 4, they're too easy;

01:02:32.590 --> 01:02:37.000
level 15 is too difficult. And
the only thing we can do that

01:02:37.000 --> 01:02:40.480
is tweak these three
levels, and ship the episode

01:02:40.480 --> 01:02:42.830
with 15 levels.

01:02:42.830 --> 01:02:46.930
So we have no guarantee for the
sort of just-right measurement.

01:02:46.930 --> 01:02:50.110
We only know that we were
able to improve, hopefully,

01:02:50.110 --> 01:02:52.840
Levels 3, 4, and 15.

01:02:52.840 --> 01:02:56.240
We would like to improve this.

01:02:56.240 --> 01:02:57.940
And that's our problem.

01:02:57.940 --> 01:03:00.022
And you can see that
at least seven days--

01:03:00.022 --> 01:03:01.480
probably a little
bit more --taking

01:03:01.480 --> 01:03:05.418
the time of the level designers,
is taken in just balancing.

01:03:08.840 --> 01:03:12.440
So how can we
improve play testing?

01:03:12.440 --> 01:03:15.170
How can we improve the speed
of play testing, accuracy,

01:03:15.170 --> 01:03:17.020
everything?

01:03:17.020 --> 01:03:20.880
With the recent breakthrough
in AI and games,

01:03:20.880 --> 01:03:23.150
we thought, OK,
maybe we can build

01:03:23.150 --> 01:03:28.310
a bot that can play like a
human-- imitate human play.

01:03:28.310 --> 01:03:30.320
So this is an
interesting AI problem,

01:03:30.320 --> 01:03:33.950
because everything
we've heard so far

01:03:33.950 --> 01:03:37.430
would suggest that we should
build Alpha Candy Zero,

01:03:37.430 --> 01:03:39.320
the best Candy player ever.

01:03:39.320 --> 01:03:40.470
But that's not the problem.

01:03:40.470 --> 01:03:44.360
We want to find an AI bot that
can play the game in the most

01:03:44.360 --> 01:03:47.210
human-like way.

01:03:47.210 --> 01:03:48.620
So what did we do?

01:03:51.330 --> 01:03:52.580
We started gathering data.

01:03:52.580 --> 01:03:55.040
That's always the first step.

01:03:55.040 --> 01:03:56.690
We tracked data from players.

01:03:56.690 --> 01:03:58.760
We tracked the
state action pair.

01:03:58.760 --> 01:04:01.010
For every action
they could take,

01:04:01.010 --> 01:04:02.860
we recorded everything
in the level,

01:04:02.860 --> 01:04:06.710
the home state, and
the action taken.

01:04:06.710 --> 01:04:09.180
This we can fit--

01:04:09.180 --> 01:04:11.700
we tracked a bunch of this
data from all of our players

01:04:11.700 --> 01:04:13.600
over some time period.

01:04:13.600 --> 01:04:17.400
And then we can fit that into
a convolutional neural network,

01:04:17.400 --> 01:04:22.840
which is the usual approach
for image recognition.

01:04:22.840 --> 01:04:25.950
And we can train a
supervised policy network

01:04:25.950 --> 01:04:28.080
based on this, a
network that can

01:04:28.080 --> 01:04:31.170
learn from the input,
the state, and predict

01:04:31.170 --> 01:04:37.710
the most common human
move in that position.

01:04:37.710 --> 01:04:39.990
And what we do
when we have this,

01:04:39.990 --> 01:04:42.090
then we can use
this policy network

01:04:42.090 --> 01:04:44.760
that plays like a human.

01:04:44.760 --> 01:04:48.070
We can upload that
to some cloud,

01:04:48.070 --> 01:04:49.920
and let it play the game--

01:04:49.920 --> 01:04:53.490
the new content of the game
--the new levels several times

01:04:53.490 --> 01:04:55.873
to give us estimate of the
difficulty of new levels.

01:04:59.580 --> 01:05:03.710
So can we have a video here?

01:05:03.710 --> 01:05:09.380
So on the right, we see the
bot playing the same level

01:05:09.380 --> 01:05:12.170
I showed you before.

01:05:12.170 --> 01:05:15.680
On top left, we see
the communication.

01:05:15.680 --> 01:05:21.110
So the agent playing the
level sends the state

01:05:21.110 --> 01:05:23.930
to a policy network that
gives back, OK, I think

01:05:23.930 --> 01:05:25.070
you should play this move.

01:05:25.070 --> 01:05:27.830
It's the most human
move in the position.

01:05:27.830 --> 01:05:31.090
And the bottom left, we show
the tracking-- actually now,

01:05:31.090 --> 01:05:35.010
we're tracking the bot instead
of the humans as we did.

01:05:35.010 --> 01:05:39.950
And you see that the bot
is playing quite well

01:05:39.950 --> 01:05:41.470
in this level.

01:05:41.470 --> 01:05:45.070
And we tried these levels
ourselves a few times.

01:05:45.070 --> 01:05:50.640
And the bot was actually better
than some of us in the team.

01:05:50.640 --> 01:05:54.340
This was very
interesting, but normal

01:05:54.340 --> 01:05:59.099
if we believe that it is
learning the actual play.

01:05:59.099 --> 01:06:00.890
And it was able to
solve the level in this.

01:06:00.890 --> 01:06:02.788
If you go back to the slides.

01:06:11.420 --> 01:06:19.450
And so this is the framework we
had in Google Cloud Platform.

01:06:19.450 --> 01:06:23.260
And I said I wanted to come back
to the setup we had for our A/B

01:06:23.260 --> 01:06:27.010
test framework, where
we learned that it

01:06:27.010 --> 01:06:30.340
was so important to
have a framework that

01:06:30.340 --> 01:06:34.860
can work fast and reliably,
and give fast iteration loops.

01:06:34.860 --> 01:06:38.590
That is exactly the problem
we had with our play testing

01:06:38.590 --> 01:06:40.210
solution.

01:06:40.210 --> 01:06:42.850
In this era of AI
and machine learning,

01:06:42.850 --> 01:06:46.540
it's rather easy to come
up with interesting ideas

01:06:46.540 --> 01:06:48.730
to improve your business--

01:06:48.730 --> 01:06:50.957
improve your processes
--but then you're

01:06:50.957 --> 01:06:51.790
left with something.

01:06:51.790 --> 01:06:53.510
You have a proof of concept.

01:06:53.510 --> 01:06:56.020
You have a test environment.

01:06:56.020 --> 01:06:58.930
But it's not creating real
value for the business

01:06:58.930 --> 01:07:03.640
until it's a production,
a product which

01:07:03.640 --> 01:07:07.540
is scalable, and stable, and
all these things that you need.

01:07:10.790 --> 01:07:14.690
And we realized that we
were a rather small team.

01:07:14.690 --> 01:07:17.020
We had this test
environment where everybody

01:07:17.020 --> 01:07:19.630
was fighting for resources--

01:07:19.630 --> 01:07:21.280
different games
than Candy Crush.

01:07:21.280 --> 01:07:23.260
We wanted to test out more.

01:07:23.260 --> 01:07:24.430
So we had to move it.

01:07:24.430 --> 01:07:26.260
We moved it to Google
Cloud Platform,

01:07:26.260 --> 01:07:32.510
and it was surprisingly
easy and surprisingly fast.

01:07:32.510 --> 01:07:34.776
So this is the setup we have.

01:07:34.776 --> 01:07:37.360
I don't have a pointer on this.

01:07:37.360 --> 01:07:40.450
You can see on the
top right that's

01:07:40.450 --> 01:07:43.520
the UI for the level designers.

01:07:43.520 --> 01:07:48.160
Then we have an API service
that talks to the Google Cloud

01:07:48.160 --> 01:07:51.070
Platform, where we
have cloud Pub/Sub,

01:07:51.070 --> 01:07:57.490
and cloud data flow to sort of
plan and distribute the work.

01:07:57.490 --> 01:08:05.380
The game engine agent
lives in Kubernetes,

01:08:05.380 --> 01:08:08.230
where we can have
hundreds of agents playing

01:08:08.230 --> 01:08:12.070
the game, basically working
as hundreds of play testers,

01:08:12.070 --> 01:08:18.550
and they communicate with the
model serving with the policy

01:08:18.550 --> 01:08:20.819
network that feeds
back the suggested

01:08:20.819 --> 01:08:23.300
human moves in each position.

01:08:23.300 --> 01:08:25.699
So that's how we
can sort of evaluate

01:08:25.699 --> 01:08:27.990
the difficulty of newer levels
with this kind of setup.

01:08:31.450 --> 01:08:32.020
OK.

01:08:32.020 --> 01:08:34.180
So what does it mean
for our business?

01:08:34.180 --> 01:08:40.300
Before, we had this,
and now we have

01:08:40.300 --> 01:08:42.760
something like this,
where the level

01:08:42.760 --> 01:08:45.970
designers are able to have
very fast iteration loops.

01:08:45.970 --> 01:08:50.819
And as I said before, that is
the key to value for business.

01:08:50.819 --> 01:08:52.420
The value for
business is not being

01:08:52.420 --> 01:08:54.620
able to prove that
there is a solution.

01:08:54.620 --> 01:08:57.960
It's being able to create
the solution very fast.

01:08:57.960 --> 01:09:01.660
So level designers are now
able to iterate on their level

01:09:01.660 --> 01:09:04.180
design.

01:09:04.180 --> 01:09:07.830
And what used to take up to
seven days of play testing

01:09:07.830 --> 01:09:10.899
takes now about seven minutes.

01:09:10.899 --> 01:09:15.010
And this allows level
designers to focus

01:09:15.010 --> 01:09:18.399
more on innovation and creation,
and being creative instead

01:09:18.399 --> 01:09:20.920
of focusing on the balance.

01:09:20.920 --> 01:09:23.520
They can just test
that very quickly.

01:09:23.520 --> 01:09:28.600
And we're hoping that this will
help Candy Crush and our games

01:09:28.600 --> 01:09:31.969
to stay on top for at
least another five years.

